Identify {= tool =}+ tools as public AI humanizer, AI text rewriting, paraphrasing, AI detector-adjacent, or AI writing-refinement products or clearly dedicated product/tool surfaces; for each tool, cover each of the {= evidence_facet =} external evidence facets listed below with a public non-ordinary-vendor source (i.e. {= url =}+ URL per `tool` / `evidence_facet` combination) that substantiates the relevant product identity, workflow, access, operational channel, or posture trace.

The point is public provenance in a commercially noisy software category where vendor pages are useful for official tool qualification but too easy as repeated facet evidence. Detector/originality language is evidence of what a source says, not a test of whether any detector can be bypassed, which tool works best, or how to use one.

Evidence facets, which we refer to as `evidence_facet`, are:
- `external_product_identity`: current external or platform-side identity for the named tool as an AI humanizer, rewriter, paraphraser, detector-adjacent product, or writing-refinement tool; this is the only external evidence facet that a generic AI-tool profile or directory page can satisfy.
- `external_workflow_capability`: independent or non-vendor-authored detail about the tool's concrete rewriting, paraphrasing, humanization, tone/style, multilingual, upload/paste, custom-voice, or comparable transformation workflow.
- `external_pricing_or_access_terms`: explicit price, free/trial availability, plan, limit, quota, app-store access, platform access, or comparable access term from an external platform or dated independent source.
- `operational_channel_or_integration`: live platform, app/plugin store, package/API ecosystem, integration catalog, automation connector, install channel, extension, endpoint, or comparable operational/developer/business trace outside ordinary vendor marketing.
- `detector_originality_or_responsible_use_discussion`: substantive public discussion of detector, originality, AI-authorship, bypass/undetectable, non-bypass, transparency, disclosure, academic-integrity, watermark, false-positive, no-guarantee, refund, or responsible-use posture.

A valid `tool` is a named standalone product or clearly dedicated tool surface in this task's domain. Generic broad-suite modules, utility cards, menu items, adjacent writing/SEO utilities, translators, summarizers, citation/reference generators, title or meta-description generators, punctuation/spell checkers, and similar surfaces are invalid unless public evidence ties that specific surface to AI humanization, rewriting, paraphrasing, detector/originality, or writing refinement in a non-incidental way. Multiple tools from the same vendor can count only when each tool has its own dedicated product/tool page, official platform/app listing, or clearly labeled page section that identifies that specific tool surface. The cited facet page itself must visibly carry enough content to evaluate the claim. Ordinary vendor-owned homepages, product pages, feature pages, pricing pages, docs/help pages, API pages, blogs, changelogs, policies, terms, and disclaimers do not satisfy these external facet sources merely because they are public or current; generic search pages, category/list pages, account signup flows, contact lookup surfaces, outreach pages, and source pages used only for rankings, recommendations, absence notes, or detector-evasion advice are outside this task's evidence object. A generic AI-tool directory, catalog, software-profile, or product-profile page can serve only the narrow `external_product_identity` role when it is dedicated and current enough for that tool; the same profile page does not supply workflow, pricing/access, operational channel, or posture evidence through badges, feature chips, short generated blurbs, "visit website" links, outbound URLs, category labels, vendor-supplied copy, or generic "free", "premium", "API", or "available" markers.

Requirements:
- The page must clearly identify the named tool or identify the vendor/product relationship that makes the named tool unambiguous. For suite-level pages, app/extension pages, directory profiles, reviews, software profiles, marketplace listings, articles, discussions, or ecosystem pages, the page must identify or clearly bind the named tool surface. Suite-wide language such as "all tools included," "apps," "browser extensions," "AI writing tools," "API for teams," generic detector/plagiarism bundles, generic plan names, broad API availability, or a many-tool category entry does not satisfy tool match for every module or every listed product.
- The page must be an external, platform, independent, ecosystem, user-review, discussion, article, software-profile, marketplace, app-store, package, integration-catalog, or comparable public trace outside ordinary vendor-owned homepage/product/pricing/docs/help/API/blog/policy marketing. Broad category, directory, search, roundup, or list pages whose only tool-specific content is a name, category label, ranking card, or short blurb are not enough. A generic AI-tool profile/directory/listing page is eligible only for the identity facet; it fails the other external facets unless the cited page visibly has a different facet-specific source context rather than a catalog profile context.
- The page must make its facet-appropriate source context visible: for `external_product_identity`, a dedicated external profile, review, article, marketplace/app/package listing, or comparable current tool-specific entry; for `external_workflow_capability`, independent or non-vendor-authored review, comparison, article, user-review, hands-on software profile, or discussion text with concrete workflow detail beyond a one-sentence category blurb, generated directory profile, or vendor-supplied listing copy; for `external_pricing_or_access_terms`, explicit platform-controlled price/access fields or independent/current dated pricing, plan, free/trial, quota, usage-limit, app-store price/access, or comparable access information tied to the named tool, not merely generic free/freemium/premium/paid badges, category labels, or profile summaries; for `operational_channel_or_integration`, a dated marketplace, integration catalog, app/plugin store, automation directory, public package/API ecosystem page, developer platform page, public extension/app listing, endpoint/package/version page, or comparable trace that makes the API, extension, app, connector, integration, install channel, endpoint, package, or deployment channel operationally visible; a directory/profile page's "visit website" link, outbound URL, homepage link, generic feature chip, or "API available" marker is not enough; for `detector_originality_or_responsible_use_discussion`, a dated review, comparison, benchmark, hands-on software profile, educational/safety article, user-review, or comparable public discussion that substantively discusses the tool's detector/originality, AI-authorship, bypass, non-bypass, transparency, disclosure, academic-integrity, false-positive, no-guarantee, refund, watermark, or responsible-use posture. Vendor-supplied marketplace/profile copy alone does not satisfy workflow, pricing, operational, or posture facets.
- The page must supply visible currentness or date context tied to the named tool and selected facet: date, update, version, listing, review, publication, platform state, price/access field, install/update metadata, package/version metadata, thread date, or similar current-availability context. A category page's overall publication date does not make every listed tool/facet current.
- The page must state the evidence matching the selected `evidence_facet`: for `external_product_identity`, product/category identity for the exact tool; for `external_workflow_capability`, a concrete rewrite/humanization/input-output workflow or capability tied to that tool; for `external_pricing_or_access_terms`, pricing, plan, free/trial, usage-limit, word/request-limit, or comparable access information from the required pricing/access source context; for `operational_channel_or_integration`, a concrete API/developer surface, extension, app/plugin, automation, integration, public package, endpoint, install/update channel, white-label/reseller, or enterprise deployment channel from an operational source context; for `detector_originality_or_responsible_use_discussion`, substantive detector/originality/AI-authorship/bypass/undetectable discussion or concrete non-bypass, transparency, disclosure, academic-integrity, false-positive, no-guarantee, refund, watermark, or responsible-use posture tied to the tool.
